  <text xml:lang="en">
    <body>
      <div>
        <head>Introduction</head>
        <p>Early work on channel-independent forecasting<ref type="bibr" target="#b0">Smith et al. (2020)</ref> established the baseline approach.</p>
        <p>Later, <ref type="bibr" target="#b1">Jones and Lee (2021)</ref> proposed an extension that also leveraged channel-independence for multivariate data.</p>
      </div>
      <figure xml:id="fig_1">
        <head>Figure 1</head>
        <figDesc>Architecture diagram.</figDesc>
        <p>𝑥 ∈ ℝ 𝑛×𝑑 𝑀 ⊗ 𝑥 encoder ℝ output 𝑦 ∈ ℝ</p>
      </figure>
      <div>
        <head>Method</head>
        <p>Task Definition Since<ref type="bibr" target="#b2">Zeng et al. (2023)</ref> </p>
        <p>and<ref type="bibr" target="#b3">Nie et al. (2022)</ref> </p>
        <p>have verified that channel-independence works well for time series, we adopt the same convention.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <head>Related</head>
        <p>Earlier, Brown et al. (2019) demonstrated a related channel-independent architecture on audio signals.</p>
      </div>
